# =============================================================================
# .dockerignore — Files to Exclude from Docker Build Context
# =============================================================================
#
# WHAT IS THE BUILD CONTEXT?
#   When you run `docker build .`, Docker sends the entire current directory
#   to the Docker daemon as the "build context". The Dockerfile's COPY
#   instructions can only copy files that were included in this context.
#
# WHY EXCLUDE FILES?
#   1. Speed: A smaller context transfers faster. node_modules alone can be
#      hundreds of MB and takes seconds to send.
#   2. Security: The .env file contains secrets (passwords, API keys).
#      You NEVER want secrets baked into a Docker image — they'd be readable
#      by anyone who pulls the image.
#   3. Correctness: The database file from your development machine should
#      NOT end up inside the production image. The container uses a volume-
#      mounted database instead.
#   4. Reproducibility: Build tools and dev dependencies shouldn't leak
#      into the production image.
#
# SYNTAX (same as .gitignore):
#   *          → wildcard (any characters)
#   **         → recursive wildcard (any depth)
#   /path      → relative to the build context root
#   !path      → negate — include this file even if a parent pattern excludes it
# =============================================================================


# ── Node.js dependencies ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# node_modules is rebuilt inside the container by `npm ci` in the Dockerfile.
# Including it would be slow (large) and possibly wrong (native binaries built
# for your OS won't run in the Alpine Linux container).
node_modules
**/node_modules


# ── Environment and secrets ───────────────────────────────────────────────────
# NEVER include .env in a Docker image. It contains passwords and API keys.
# Environment variables are injected at runtime via docker-compose.yml.
.env
.env.*
!.env.example     # Exception: include the template (it has no real secrets)


# ── Database files ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# The production database lives on a Docker volume, not inside the image.
*.db
*.db-shm          # SQLite WAL mode shared memory file
*.db-wal          # SQLite WAL mode write-ahead log file
backups/


# ── Version control ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Git metadata doesn't belong in a container image.
.git
.gitignore


# ── Development / editor files ────────────────────────────────────────────────
.DS_Store         # macOS metadata files
Thumbs.db         # Windows metadata files
*.log             # Log files from local development
.vscode/          # VS Code workspace settings
.idea/            # JetBrains IDE settings
*.swp             # Vim swap files
*.swo


# ── CI/CD and documentation ───────────────────────────────────────────────────
# These are useful on the host but waste space in the image.
.github/
*.md
!README.md        # Exception: keep the README in the image (harmless, informative)


# ── Test files ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
test/
tests/
*.test.js
*.spec.js
coverage/


# ── Deploy config (already copied into the image where needed) ────────────────
# The deploy/ directory is only needed for docker-compose, not inside the container.
deploy/
docker-compose*.yml
Dockerfile*
